So yes, repentance is personal, but in the Bible it often contains a corporate element and an element of moving in the opposite direction.

19:53.346 --> 20:04.521
It's often described as individuals and communities turning away from things that violate God's purposes like idolatry or injustice or exploitation or selfishness.

20:05.182 --> 20:09.027
But that is only step one in repentance.

20:09.048 --> 20:22.546
Step two is to turn towards faithful living centered in worship of the Most High God, lived out with devotion, lived out with love, lived out in the practice of justice, lived out in harmony with others and producing good.

20:22.978 --> 20:36.218
So if the context for when Jesus originally said this parable was the questions about why certain people had a certain faith, these questions of evil, Jesus kind of gives us the ultimate Jesus joke here.

20:36.238 --> 20:38.241
He says, don't think about it that way.

20:39.003 --> 20:43.149
He says, instead think about you and your own need for repentance.

20:44.651 --> 20:51.602
Jesus, he doesn't pull the prosperity gospel move either and say that if you follow this path that you will be free from calamity,

20:52.386 --> 20:54.870
But he says, no, this is what you need to think about.

20:54.890 --> 20:57.995
You need to think about your own need for repentance.

20:58.015 --> 21:01.361
Don't think about false assurances that everything is going to be okay.

21:01.862 --> 21:07.551
He recognizes that life is fragile, but it does demand urgency in the midst of opportunity.

21:09.153 --> 21:19.250
So rather than focusing on the gravity of other transgressions or mistakes, which we all want to do, Jesus says to instead think about how you are producing good.

21:19.810 --> 21:24.335
Don't try to describe blame to certain situations or punishments or rewards or any of that.

21:24.415 --> 21:25.957
Don't think about others.

21:26.017 --> 21:29.481
He says, ensure that you are not missing your own fruit.

21:31.162 --> 21:32.043
Are you missing fruit?

21:32.544 --> 21:33.905
That is what you need to pay attention to.

21:34.246 --> 21:37.009
Let other stuff in those other people, you can't control that.

21:37.029 --> 21:37.970
You can't control them.

21:37.990 --> 21:43.176
But what you can control is your heart and the fruit that comes from it.

21:43.196 --> 21:46.880
And we have a book at home that Penny loves for us to read to her before bed.

21:47.240 --> 21:49.042
And it's called, What is God Like?

21:49.250 --> 21:51.653
Maybe you've read it too to your kids, it's a great book.

21:51.713 --> 21:57.399
And the premise of the book is that very question in the title, what is God like?

21:58.160 --> 22:04.908
And it says, that is a very big question that people from places all around the world have wondered about since the beginning of time.

22:05.829 --> 22:13.618
And while nobody has seen all of God, because God is far too big for any of us to fully see, we can know what God is like.

22:14.178 --> 22:28.661
And it lists all these things from scripture that we can know about God, that God is like an eagle, God is like a fort, God is like three dancers, God is like the wind, a mother, a father, but Penny's favorite one is where it says this.

22:28.741 --> 22:32.727
It says, God is like a gardener, patient and nurturing.

22:33.368 --> 22:40.158
God plants, waters, weeds and fertilizes the earth until every good thing on it seeks the nourishing sun and grows.

22:41.741 --> 22:42.482
And I think

22:43.138 --> 22:50.529
She likes this one and she gets this one because we have a garden in our backyard that Penny loves to work on.

22:50.549 --> 22:52.091
I brought a couple photos.

22:52.131 --> 22:54.635
There's our part of our broccoli haul.

22:55.897 --> 22:58.000
And then we also had a lot of extra basil.

22:58.160 --> 23:04.109
So Penny went around the neighborhood with her shopping cart and delivered basil to our neighbors.

23:05.531 --> 23:10.278
And it's because of the care that we put into our garden as a family and mostly Julia.

23:11.600 --> 23:13.042
But because of this,

23:13.762 --> 23:16.686
Penny knows a little bit of what God is like.

23:18.429 --> 23:25.660
And as we go through our lives and try to answer the question of what is God like, we can see in this parable that God is like a gardener.

23:26.681 --> 23:29.325
And what does the gardener do in this story?

23:29.385 --> 23:31.769
He counsels patience and mercy.

23:32.850 --> 23:34.072
You know what else he doesn't say?

23:34.112 --> 23:37.477
He doesn't say, the tree better figure this all out on their own.

23:37.557 --> 23:42.244
I'm gonna give him a year if things are not settled by then, you know, it's fine.

23:42.985 --> 23:43.346
No.

23:43.618 --> 23:46.182
The tree has not been left to its own devices.

23:46.222 --> 23:55.997
The gardener is willing to do everything that is required to get the tree to a healthy place, to get it to act as it should to help it produce fruit.

23:56.959 --> 24:00.545
And just like the gardener in the story, Jesus is patient with us.

24:01.747 --> 24:10.000
He will do what we need to help us grow because God does not leave us on our own or tell us to rely on our own resources.

24:10.080 --> 24:11.602
He is willing to be patient.

24:12.002 --> 24:13.244
He's willing to care for us.

24:13.304 --> 24:18.671
He is willing to water us and to give us the opportunity to seize His graciousness.

24:20.253 --> 24:28.864
But as Jesus makes it clear, two times leading up to this parable, the part that we have to play is one of repentance.

24:30.446 --> 24:37.155
Not a shallow repentance or one that's overly focused on morality or expressions of regret.

24:38.396 --> 24:39.858
We see here along with

24:40.002 --> 24:50.255
many other places in the Bible is that it refers to a changed mind, a new way of seeing things being persuaded to adopt a different perspective.

24:51.457 --> 25:01.049
Repentance is not only about more expressions of piety, but it is a new way of entering into the world and its arcs towards joy.

25:02.211 --> 25:07.698
It's about an entirely reoriented self-one that is now oriented towards God's kingdom.

25:08.610 --> 25:15.939
And so I wonder for you and for each one of us here today, what is it that you might need to change your mind about today?

25:17.641 --> 25:24.389
What are the areas of your life that you are holding onto that might need to be reoriented to God's kingdom way?

25:25.490 --> 25:27.833
Could it be in your relationships?

25:28.534 --> 25:33.040
Could it be with how you think about work or how often you work?

25:33.760 --> 25:35.663
Could it be with your finances?

25:35.763 --> 25:38.386
Could it be with how generous you are?

25:38.754 --> 25:43.101
There be an idol in your life taking away devotion to God and one of those things.

25:43.141 --> 25:45.986
Could it be how you think about civic engagement?

25:46.006 --> 25:48.130
Could it be in complicity to injustice?

25:48.270 --> 25:52.858
I know that I can answer some form of yes to all of those questions for me.

25:52.918 --> 26:00.370
So it might be good to seek discernment where God might be speaking to you today and want to change your mind.

26:01.538 --> 26:12.030
And in light of us observing this season of creation, we might just start this journey of repentance for how we have treated and neglected and abused the rest of God's good creation.

26:12.711 --> 26:18.898
Whether we've done so knowingly or in ignorance, we have been complicit in our abuse of the land and of our neighbors.

26:20.340 --> 26:24.525
There are a few Oregonian pastors and professors up at George Fox.

26:24.565 --> 26:25.426
Their names are

26:25.538 --> 26:28.242
Jennifer Butler, Daniel Brunner, and A.J.

26:28.262 --> 26:38.957
Swaboda, and they wrote a lot about this topic and they argue that the only way that things can improve is through a radical spiritual change in our hearts and our communities.

26:39.918 --> 26:48.370
They say we must develop a new way of seeing the world and the archetype for the radical response that is needed is found in the Bible as repentance.

26:49.090 --> 27:07.753
that as we change our minds, whether it is from intentional abuse or overconsumption or just not thinking that ecological living is a Christian imperative or important to our faith, we have to choose to be continually converted to repent of our participation in perpetuating the crisis and respond with acts of healing.

27:09.075 --> 27:17.906
They put it like this, whenever Christians and Christian communities repent for our trespasses against the earth, we also ought to be engaging in actions of restitution.

27:18.370 --> 27:25.239
From planting gardens to ride share programs for worship gatherings, Christ followers are finding creative ways to practice restitution.

27:25.980 --> 27:40.160
If dry earth, bellowing cattle, and withering vines are a sign of humanity's sinfulness against the land, perhaps water conservation projects, content chickens in the coop, and flowering gardens are signs of repentance, restitution, and conversion.

27:41.682 --> 27:44.946
So when we do things like turning guns into garden tools,

27:45.218 --> 27:51.584
and use those tools to provide food for our neighbors, that is what repentance looks like.

27:52.345 --> 28:01.073
Taking something that was heading in one direction, heading towards violence and turning it around and sending it in the other way and providing restitution and reconciliation.

28:01.113 --> 28:06.458
Something meant for harm and in light of God's kingdom, turning it into something that builds and grows.

28:07.880 --> 28:14.706
Repentance is necessary for our complicity and complacency, for our explanations and for our enabling.

28:15.330 --> 28:24.403
If our repentance doesn't move beyond saying sorry to living a life of restoration and reconciliation, we might just be missing the mark.

28:25.805 --> 28:32.314
And for me, repentance can be a scary word, probably you too, especially when it says in bold letters, repent or perish.

28:33.255 --> 28:39.864
But when I can give it hand holds, even in this one area, it doesn't sound as scary to me.

28:40.545 --> 28:44.050
It doesn't sound as undonting or undoable.

28:44.770 --> 28:54.841
Like our tree outside, maybe we have had seasons where we are green and full of life and producing fruit, where our hearts and our lives reflect the kingdom of God.

28:56.022 --> 28:58.886
But sometimes we look like that tree does right now.

28:59.847 --> 29:04.492
A little sad, a little unhealthy, and not doing what we were made to do.

29:05.493 --> 29:13.682
But Jesus doesn't count us out because I know that as we take these steps of repentance, Jesus the gardener will be there right along the way.

29:14.050 --> 29:17.338
with water and fertilizer making us new again.

29:17.378 --> 29:26.039
So Antioch family, may we be a people of repentance as we join our hands with God the gardener to make all things new.

29:26.761 --> 29:27.122
Amen.

